    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey my realtor just mentioned i need to set up an escrow account for this house i'm buying in toronto. i'm kinda confused. whats escrow actually and why do i need it for the closing?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Escrow is a neutral third-party account where funds and documents are held securely until all conditions of the sale are met, ensuring neither the buyer nor the seller gets ripped off. In Toronto, this is standard practice because the real estate market is complex, and you need a buffer zone to protect your money while the lawyer or title company handles the final checks. Without it, your cash would be sitting in a risky spot, and the transaction could fall apart if a title issue or inspection problem arises.\n\nThink of it like a vault that only opens when everyone agrees the deal is good to go. It's not just for the money; it's also for the paperwork, ensuring that the transfer of ownership happens exactly when the contract says it should. If you skip this step, you're essentially handing over your hard-earned cash directly to the seller without the safety net of a professional intermediary, which is a recipe for disaster.\n\nIt's a bit like a construction site where the foreman holds the blueprints until the foundation is poured correctly. You don't want to pour the whole foundation before checking the soil, right? The escrow agent acts as that foreman, making sure everything is in order before the keys are handed over. It's",
