    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "thats a helpful analogy. so basically the escrow agent is just sitting there guarding the money until everything is ready? sounds a bit like they're just a middleman holding onto my cash for no reason other than to keep it safe. is there any risk of something going wrong with the person holding it?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "You're absolutely right to be curious about the \"middleman\" aspect, and honestly, that's exactly what they are in a way—a trusted custodian, not just a passive holder. In the world of Toronto real estate, the escrow agent (often a lawyer or a specialized trust company) is legally bound by strict fiduciary duties to keep your funds separate from their own accounts and to release them only when the contract conditions are perfectly met.\n\nThe risk of them going \"missing\" is incredibly low because these institutions are heavily regulated by the Ontario Real Estate Association and the Financial Services Regulatory Authority. They aren't just \"holding cash for no reason\"; they are acting as a security layer that prevents the seller from getting their money before the buyer's conditions (like inspections or financing) are satisfied, and vice versa.\n\nThink of it like a very strict, armored courier service that only drops off a package when both the sender and receiver have signed off on a specific checklist. If the courier tried to steal the package, they'd face massive legal consequences and reputational damage that would end their career overnight. In fact, if the escrow agent makes a mistake, the transaction usually stalls, giving you time to fix it rather than losing",
